nd tolerate ones peers prepares a child for life in a way no home education ever could. &#10;Not if you just do not get the complex rules of teenage interaction. Tthe massive hit on self-esteem of daily social failure blights the present and endangers the future. Quality of interaction is more important than quality. &#10;Children brought up in this way run a great risk of ending up as isolated, unhappy oddballs- as I strongly suspect most of their parents are. &#10;Mixing up cause and effect, pal. G'way and find something to comment on that you know something about. "/><type4:DocumentMetaData xmi:id="13" sofa="1" begin="0" end="861" language="en" documentId="1158" isLastSegment="false"/><types:WebArgumentMetadata xmi:id="24" sofa="1" begin="0" end="0" author="easterman" date="29 July 2010 3:40pm" docType="artcomment" origUrl="http://discussion.theguardian.com/comment-permalink/6886164" topic="homeschooling" thumbsUp="7" thumbsDown="0" origId="1158" notes="" title="Home education: precious, not dangerous"/><type6:Paragraph xmi:id="39" sofa="1" begin="0" end="107"/><type6:Paragraph xmi:id="43" sofa="1" begin="108" end="253"/><type6:Paragraph xmi:id="47" sofa="1" begin="254" end="387"/><type6:Paragraph xmi:id="51" sofa="1" begin="388" end="614"/><type6:Paragraph xmi:id="55" sofa="1" begin="615" end="757"/><type6:Paragraph xmi:id="59" sofa="1" begin="758" end="861"/><cas:View sofa="1" members="13 24 39 43 47 51 55 59"/></xmi:XMI>